    <body>
        <div xml:id="KT19-kilavi">
          <p type="edition">uṇarppuvayiṉ vārā ūṭaṟkaṇ talaimakaṉ colliyatu.</p>
          <p type="translation" xml:lang="en">Uttered by HIM in love-quarrel before regaining mental clarity.</p>
          </div>

        <div xml:id="KT19">
            <lg type="edition">
<l>                evvi yiḻanta vaṟumaiyāḻp pāṇar</l>
<l>                pūvil vaṟuntalai pōlap pulleṉ</l>
<l>                ṟiṉaimati vāḻiya neñcē maṉaimarat</l>
<l>                telluṟu mauva ṉāṟum</l>
<l>                palliruṅ kūntal yāraḷō namakkē.</l>
             </lg>
            <lg type="translation" xml:lang="en">
                <l rend="indent">Like the head, poor without flowers,</l>
                <l rend="indent">
                    <choice>
                        <seg>of the poor lute-player who has lost Evvi,</seg>
                        <seg>of the lute-player, poor since he lost Evvi,</seg>
                    </choice>
                </l>
                <l>despair, go on, heart!</l>
                <l>[She with] many<note place="foot"><term xml:lang="ta">pal</term> in this connection is explained by TVG as a hint to the five ways of doing the hair on one head as described by Nacc. in his commentary to Cīvak. 2437.</note> dark tresses,</l>
                <l rend="indent">fragrant from fair wild jasmine of the tree near the house(?)</l>
                <l rend="indent4">–who [is] she to us?</l>




             </lg>
        </div>
    </body>
